Philippine Stocks: DMCI Holdings, PAL, Petron Corp., Semirara

-- B y   I a n   C .   S a y s o n
-- 
2011-03-08T04:53:02Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-08/philippine-stocks-dmci-holdings-petron-corp-semirara.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual price changes in Philippine trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses, and prices are as of the noon close in
Manila.  The Philippine Stock Exchange Index rose 0.3 percent to
3,898.87, the highest since Jan. 28.    PAL Holdings Inc. (PAL)  , owner of the nation’s biggest
airline, decreased 3.4 percent to 5.05 pesos, the lowest since
Jan. 12. The employees union of its unit Philippine Airlines
Inc. has filed a notice to hold a strike, Manila Standard Today
reported, citing Gerry Rivera, president of the union.  Rivera couldn’t be reached on his mobile phone for comment.
PAL President Jaime Bautista couldn’t be reached on his mobile
phone for comment.    Petron Corp. (PCOR)  , the largest of two oil refiners in
the country, sank 2.7 percent to 15.18 pesos, the steepest loss
since Feb. 22. The government asked  oil companies  to step up oil
imports and maintain a minimum 15-day “in-country” inventory,
Energy Secretary Rene Almendras said. Oil futures in  New York 
have climbed 15 percent this year.    Semirara Mining Corp. (SCC)  , the largest coal producer,
advanced 5.1 percent to 214.20 pesos, the highest based on
prices going back to March 1999. The company will develop the
site of a power plant in the province of Batangas into an
economic zone to attract clients with high electricity
requirements, a stock exchange filing showed.    DMCI Holdings Inc. (DMC)  , the nation’s biggest
construction company and owner of Semirara, climbed 4.8 percent
to 37.20 pesos, the highest since Nov. 22.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ian C. Sayson in Manila at 
 isayson@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
